--- title: "Interactive Data Visualization: ggiraph vs plotly" description: "A comparison of dynamic visualization approaches in R." metadata: pagetitle: "Interactive Data Visualization: ggiraph vs plotly" author: "Christoph Scheuch" date: "2024-01-23" image: thumbnail.png image-alt: ... Created with DALL-E 3. --- `ggiraph` ... `plotly` ... I also use the `plotly::ggplotly()` function The types of plots that I chose for the comparison heavily draw on the examples given in [R for Data Science](https://r4ds.hadley.nz/data-visualize) - an amazing resource if you want to get started with data visualization. # Loading packages and data We start by loading the main packages of interest and the popular `penguins` data that comes with `plotly` and exists as an R package. We then use the `penguins` data frame as the data to compare all functions and methods below. Note that I drop all rows with missing values because I don't want to get into related messages in this post. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(dplyr) library(ggiraph) library(plotly) library(palmerpenguins) penguins <- na.omit(palmerpenguins::penguins) ``` ::: # A full-blown example Let"s start with an advancved example that combines many different aesthetics at the same time: we plot two columns against each other, use color and shape aesthetics do differentiate species, include separate regression lines for each species, manually set nice labels, and use a theme. As you can see in this example already, `ggiraph` and `plotly` have a fundamentally different syntactic approach. While `ggiraph` works with layers, `plotly` uses a specific function with a few parameter and additional methods. ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph Tooltip on geom_smooth_interactive cannot show esimtaed bill_length etc + confidence intervals show NA ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_full <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm, color = species, shape = species)) + geom_point_interactive( aes(tooltip = paste("bill_length_mm:", bill_length_mm, "
", "bill_depth_mm:", bill_depth_mm)), size = 2 ) + geom_smooth_interactive(method = "lm", formula = "y ~ x") + labs(x = "Bill length (mm)", y = "Bill width (mm)", title = "Bill length vs. bill width", subtitle = "Using geom_point and geom_smooth of the ggiraph package", color = "Species", shape = "Species") + theme_minimal() girafe(ggobj = fig_full) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_full <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm, color = species, shape = species)) + geom_point(size = 2) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = "y ~ x") + labs(x = "Bill length (mm)", y = "Bill width (mm)", title = "Bill length vs. bill width", subtitle = "Using geom_point and geom_smooth of the ggiraph package", color = "Species", shape = "Species") + theme_minimal() ggplotly(fig_full) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: # Visualizing distributions ## A categorical variable Let's break down the differences in smaller steps by focusing on simpler examples. If you have a categorical variable and want to compare its relevance in your data, then `ggiraph::geom_bar()` and `plotly.countplot()` are your friends. I manually specify the order in the `plotly` figure to mimic the automatic behavior of `ggiraph`. ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_categorical <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = island)) + geom_bar_interactive( aes(tooltip = paste("count:", after_stat(count))) ) girafe(ggobj = fig_categorical) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} penguins |> count(island) |> plot_ly(data = _, x = ~island, y = ~n, type = 'bar') |> layout(barmode = 'stack') ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_categorical <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = island)) + geom_bar() ggplotly(fig_categorical) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## A numerical variable If you have a numerical variable, usually histograms are a good starting point to get a better feeling for the distribution of your data. `ggiraph::geom_histogram()` and `plotly.histplot` with options to control bin widths or number of bins are the functions for this task. ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_numerical <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm)) + geom_histogram_interactive( aes(tooltip = paste("bill_length_mm:", after_stat(count))), binwidth = 2 ) girafe(ggobj = fig_numerical) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # TODO fix bin size??? plot_ly(penguins, x = ~bill_length_mm, type = "histogram", autobinx = FALSE, xbins = list(start = min(penguins$bill_length_mm), end = max(penguins$bill_length_mm), size = 2)) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_numerical <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 2) ggplotly(fig_numerical) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: Both packages also support density curves, but I personally wouldn"t recommend to start with densities because they are estimated curves that might obscure underlying data features. However, we look at densities in the next section. # Visualizing relationships ## A numerical and a categorical variable To visualize relationships, you need to have at least two columns. If you have a numerical and a categorical variable, then histograms or densities with groups are a good starting point. The next example illustrates the use of density curves via `ggiraph::geom_density()` and `plotly.kdeplot()` with similar options to control the appearance. ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # NOT POSSIBLE TO ADD paste(after_stat(density))): Aesthetics can not vary with a ribbon fig_density <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = body_mass_g, color = species, fill = species)) + geom_density_interactive( aes(tooltip = paste(species)), linewidth = 0.75, alpha = 0.5 ) girafe(ggobj = fig_density) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_density <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = body_mass_g, color = species, fill = species)) + geom_density(linewidth = 0.75, alpha = 0.5) ggplotly(fig_density) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## Two categorical columns Stacked bar plots are a good way to display the relationship between two categorical columns. `geom_bar()` with the `position` argument and `plotly.histplot()` with `stat` are your aesthetics of choice for this task. Note that you can easily switch to counts by using `position = "identity"` and `stat = "count"`, respectively, instead of relative frequencies as in the example below. Note that I use `shrink = 0.8` to get some spacing between columns in the `plotly` plot. ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph Add tooltip island via fill in paste ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # fig_two_categorical <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = species, fill = island)) + geom_bar_interactive( aes(tooltip = paste(fill, ":", after_stat(count))), position = "fill" ) girafe(ggobj = fig_two_categorical) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_two_categorical <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = species, fill = island)) + geom_bar(position = "fill") ggplotly(fig_two_categorical) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## Two numerical columns Scatter plots and regression lines are definitely the most common approach for visualizing the relationship between two numerical columns and we focus on scatter plots for this example (see the first visualization example if you want to see again how to add a regression line). Here, the `size` parameter controls the size of the shapes that you use for the data points in `ggiraph::geom_point()` relative to the base size (i.e., it is not tied to any unit of measurement like pixels). For `plotly.scatterplot()` you have the `s` parameter to control point sizes manually, where size is typically given in squared points (where a point is a unit of measure in typography, equal to 1/72 of an inch). ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_two_columns <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm)) + geom_point_interactive( aes(tooltip = paste("bill_length_mm:", bill_length_mm, "
", "flipper_length_mm:", flipper_length_mm)), size = 2 ) girafe(ggobj = fig_two_columns) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} plot_ly(data = penguins, x = ~bill_length_mm, y = ~flipper_length_mm, type = "scatter", mode = "markers", marker = list(size = 10)) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_two_columns <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm)) + geom_point(size = 2) ggplotly(fig_two_columns) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## Three or more columns You can include more information by mapping columns to additional aesthetics. For instance, we can map colors and shapes to species and create separate plots for each island by using facets. Facets are actually a great way to extend your figures, so I highly recommend playing around with them using your own data. In `ggiraph` you add the facet layer at the end, whereas in `plotly` you have to start with the facet grid at the beginning and map scatter plots across facets. Note that I use variable assignment to `penguins_facet` in order to prevent `plotly` from printing the figure twice while rendering this post (no idea why though). ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_many_columns <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm)) + geom_point_interactive( aes(color = species, shape = species, tooltip = paste("bill_length_mm:", bill_length_mm, "
", "flipper_length_mm:", flipper_length_mm, "
", "species:", species)) ) + facet_wrap(~island) girafe(ggobj = fig_many_columns) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # TODO: no idea how to add subplot headlines penguins |> group_by(island) |> group_map(~plot_ly(data = ., x = ~bill_length_mm, y = ~flipper_length_mm, color = ~species, type = "scatter", mode="markers"), .keep=TRUE) |> subplot(nrows = 1, shareX = TRUE, shareY=TRUE) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} fig_many_columns <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm)) + geom_point(aes(color = species, shape = species)) + facet_wrap(~island) ggplotly(fig_many_columns) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: # Saving plots As a final comparison, let us look at saving plots. `ggiraph::ggsave()` provides the most important options as function paramters. In `plotly`, you have to, for instance, tweak the figure size before can save the figure. ::: {.panel-tabset} ### ggiraph ::: {.cell} ::: ### plotly ::: {.cell} ::: ### ggplotly ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} penguins_figure <- penguins |> ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm)) + geom_point() ggsave(penguins_figure, filename = "penguins-figure.png", width = 7, height = 5, dpi = 300) ``` ::: ::: # Conclusion ...
